ion for [[1973\u201374 European Cup#First round|European Cup first round]]\n|result1=EC\n|col_UC=blue1|text_UC=Qualification for [[1973\u201374 UEFA Cup#First round|UEFA Cup first round]]\n|result2=UC|result3=UC\n|col_ECWC=yellow1|text_ECWC=Qualification for [[1973\u201374 European Cup Winners' Cup#First round|Cup Winners' Cup first round]]\n|result8=ECWC\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegation to [[Yugoslav Second League]]\n|result17=R|result18=R\n|update=complete\n|class_rules=1) points; 2) goal difference; 3) number of goals scored.\n|source=[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeghist.html rsssf.com] \n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n'''Champions'''<br />\n[[Red Star Belgrade]]\n\n[[Zoran Antonijevi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Jovan A\u0107imovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Zoran Bingulac]]<br />\n[[Vladislav Bogi\u0107evi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Kiril Doj\u010dinovski|Kiro Doj\u010dinovski]]<br />\n[[Ratomir Dujkovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Milovan \u0110ori\u0107]]<br />\n[[Slobodan Jankovi\u0107 (footballer)|Slobodan Jankovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[\u017divorad Jefti\u0107]]<br />\n[[Nikola Jovanovi\u0107 (footballer, born 1952)|Nikola Jovanovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Stanislav Karasi]] <br />\n[[Mihalj Keri]]<br />\n[[Branko Klenkovski]]<br />\n[[Petar Krivoku\u0107a]]<br />\n[[Vojin Lazarevi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Du\u0161an Nikoli\u0107]]<br />\n[[Mile Novkovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Miroslav Pavlovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Aleksandar Panajotovi\u0107]]<br />\n[[Vladimir Petrovi\u0107]] <br />\n[[Ognjan Petrovi\u0107]] <br />\n[[Sead Su\u0161i\u0107]]<br />\n[[Zoran Filipovi\u0107]] <br />\n[[Dragan D\u017eaji\u0107]]<br />\n<ref>[http://www.redstarbelgrade.com/historyDefault.aspx?sectionID=10&cultureID=1 Championship Winners, Red Star Belgrade official site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213050130/http://www.redstarbelgrade.com/historyDefault.aspx?sectionID=10&cultureID=1 |date=2009-12-13 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[1972\u201373 Yugoslav Second League]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeghist.html Yugoslavia Domestic Football Full Tables]\n\n{{Yugoslav First League}}\n{{1972\u201373 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1972-73 Yugoslav First League}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1972\u201373 in European association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1972\u201373 in Yugoslavian football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[Yugoslav First League|Prva savezna liga]]\n| season                     = 1972&ndash;73\n| dates = {{Nowrap|20 August 1972 \u2013 24 June 1973}}\n| winners                    = [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] (11th title)\n| relegated                  = [[FK Spartak Subotica|Spartak]]<br>[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]]\n| continentalcup1            = \n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = \n| continentalcup2            = \n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = \n| continentalcup3            = \n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = \n| league topscorer           = [[Vojin Lazarevi\u0107]]<br />[[Slobodan Santra\u010d]]<br />(25 goals each)\n| biggest home win           = \n| biggest away win           = \n| highest scoring            = \n| matches                    = \n| total goals                = \n| longest wins               = \n| longest unbeaten           = \n| longest losses             = \n| highest attendance         = \n| lowest attendance          = \n| average attendance         = \n| prevseason                 = [[1971\u201372 Yugoslav First League|1971\u201372]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1973\u201374 Yugoslav First League|1973\u201374]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1972\u201373 [[Yugoslav First League]] season''' was the 27th season of the First Federal League of Yugoslavia ({{lang-sh-Latn|Prva savezna liga Jugoslavije}}), the top level [[association football]] competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], since its establishment in 1946. A total of 18 teams competed in the league, with the [[1971\u201372 Yugoslav First League|previous season]]'s runners-up [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] winning the title.\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eighteen teams contested the league, including sixteen sides from the [[1971\u201372 Yugoslav First League|1971\u201372 season]] and two sides promoted from the 1971\u201372 [[Yugoslav Second League]] (YSL) as winners of the two second level divisions East and West. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 34 rounds. Two points were awarded for wins and one point for draws.\n\n[[FK Radni\u010dki 1923|Radni\u010dki Kragujevac]] and [[NK Maribor]] were relegated from the [[1971\u201372 Yugoslav First League]] after finishing the season in bottom two places of the league table.  The two clubs promoted to top level were [[FK Bor|Bor]] and [[FK Spartak Zlatibor Voda|Spartak Subotica]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n!width=\"130\"| Team\n!width=\"100\"| Location\n!width=\"200\"| [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia#Federal subjects|Federal Republic]] \n!width=\"90\"| Position<br />in [[1971\u201372 Yugoslav First League|1971\u201372]]\n|-\n|[[FK Bor|Bor]]\n|[[Bor, Serbia|Bor]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|[[Banja Luka]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">013</span>13th\n|-\n|[[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik]]\n|[[Zenica]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">012</span>12th\n|-\n|[[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">008</span>8th\n|-\n|[[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n|[[Split (city)|Split]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">010</span>10th\n|-\n|[[OFK Beograd|OFK Belgrade]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">003</