{"title_page": "Valtesse de La Bigne", "text_new": "{{short description|French stage actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = La Bigne, Valtesse.jpg\n| alt           = Valtesse de La Bigne, by Henri Gervex, mus\u00e9e d'Orsay, Paris\n| caption       = Valtesse de La Bigne, by [[Henri Gervex]], [[mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], Paris\n| birth_name    = \u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne\n| birth_date    = 1848\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| death_date    =  {{Death date|1910|07|29|df=y}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = French\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]], [[courtesan]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''\u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne''', known as countess '''Valtesse de La Bigne''' (1848, in [[Paris]] \u2013 29 July 1910,<ref>[http://data.bnf.fr/13510624/valtesse_de_la_bigne/ Valtesse de la Bigne \u2013 Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France].</ref> in [[Ville-d'Avray]]) was a French [[courtesan]] and [[demi-mondaine]].\n\n== Life ==\n\n===Youth and entry into prostitution===\nOne of six siblings, \u00c9milie-Louise was the daughter of a violent alcoholic father and a laundry maid from Normandy who worked as a prostitute. She worked in a Paris sweet shop at age 10 and a dress shop at 13, when she was raped in the street by an older man. She modelled for the painter [[Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot|Corot]], whose studio was in the district where she lived. At a young age she began work as a prostitute in the lorettes: \"respectable mistresses\", between the lower-class streetwalker or grisette and upper-class courtesan. Nevertheless, this was still clandestine prostitution, often in doorways, and came with the risk of police arrest or having one's head shaved as punishment or humiliation.<ref name=\"Match\">[[Claire Castillon]], [http://www.parismatch.com/Royal-Blog/royaute-francaise/Valtesse-de-la-Bigne-coucher-pour-arriver-578894 \u00ab Valtesse de la Bigne, coucher pour arriver \u00bb], ''[[Paris Match]]'', week of 31 July-6 August 2014, pages 97\u2013100.</ref>\n\nQuickly moving onto rich clients, she trained at the [[Bal Mabille]] on Sundays and worked in a women's underwear shop on the Champ-de-Mars, frequented by high-ranking officers, enabling her to dream of social climbing. There she met and fell in love with a 20-year-old man, Richard Fossey, with whom she had two children, though Fossey left her to go to Algeria two years later without marrying her as he had promised. \n\nde La Bigne entrusted her two children to her mother, who later on took them to live in the countryside. Following the death of her younger daughter while in her mother's care, de La Bigne won a public court case against her mother, who was allowing history to repeat itself as her granddaughter became increasingly drawn into the prostitution of France's demimonde. After winning custody of her one remaining daughter \u2014 with whom she became pregnant at age 16 \u2014 de La Bigne had her placed into a Catholic boarding school. Later, bitter at her loss of regular income in lieu of providing childcare, her mother assaulted de La Bigne's housekeeper Camille, a childhood friend, who also took her to court, but her case was thrown out. <ref> Catherine Hewitt, The Mistress of Paris.</ref>\n\n\u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne took the pseudonym \"Valtesse\" due to its similarity to \"Votre Altesse\" (your highness) \u2014 she later advised [[Liane de Pougy|Anne-Marie Chassaigne]] to take a pseudonym as well. She also resolved never to marry but to gain money and social position by other means. She profited from the \"br\u00e9siliens\", foreign clients visiting Paris, and aspired to join the \"archidr\u00f4lesses\", a group of courtesans.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\n[[Jacques Offenbach]] brought Valtesse to public attention with a small role at the [[Bouffes-Parisiens]] and proposed that she act in his productions.<ref name=\"Match\"/> Her debut was as Hebe in ''[[Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers]]'' \u2013 one critic judged that she was \"as red and timid as a virgin by [[Titian]].\"\n\n=== 'Courtisane du Tout-Paris' ===\n[[File:\u00c9douard Li\u00e8vre Lit de parade de Valtesse de La Bigne c. 1875 Mus\u00e9e des arts d\u00e9coratifs Paris.jpg|thumb|Valtesse de La Bigne's show bed.]]\nShe became the composer's mistress and thus gained access to fashionable restaurants like Bignon (the former [[Caf\u00e9 de Foy]]) or the [[Caf\u00e9 Tortoni de Paris|Caf\u00e9 Tortoni]], where she met [[\u00c9mile Zola|Zola]], [[Gustave Flaubert|Flaubert]] and [[Guy de Maupassant|Maupassant]]. Even the starvation of the [[siege of Paris (1870)|siege of Paris]] did not dampen her aspirations \u2013 she was made a countess by [[Napoleon III]]. Known among the [[Tout-Paris]] for his scathing humour, the journalist and writer [[Aur\u00e9lien Scholl]] wrote: \"During the siege of Paris, all the women ate dog. It was thought that this nourishment taught them the principles of fidelity. Not at all! They demanded necklaces!\"<ref name=\"Match\"/><ref>[http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/aurelien-scholl-2694.php?citations Citations d'Aur\u00e9lien Scholl], on ''evene.lefigaro.fr'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref>\n\nAt the end of the war, Valtesse quickly launched herself as a high-class courtesan, leaving Offenbach and shifting her attentions to [[House of Lubomirski|prince Lubomirski]], who installed her in an apartment in rue Saint-Georges. She wrecked it, left him and had a succession of other rich lovers, such as [[Boson de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|prince de Sagan]], whom she also bankrupted by having him build her a h\u00f4tel particulier designed by [[Jules F\u00e9vrier]] between 1873 and 1876 at 98, [[boulevard Malesherbes]], at the corner of [[rue de la Terrasse]] (destroyed and replaced by a residential block in 1904).<ref>[http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Valtesse-de-la-Bigne-coucher-pour-arriver-578894 \u00ab Valtesse de La Bigne : coucher pour arriver \u00bb], on ''parismatch.com'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref>\n\nNicknamed 'Rayon d'or' or 'golden ray', she immersed herself in art and literature. She bought a carriage to travel around Paris, and bought a sumptuous house at [[Ville-d'Avray]], which she decorated with paintings commissioned from [[\u00c9douard Detaille]] showing fictional members of her invented 'la Bigne family'.<ref name=\"Match\"/> In 1876 she published an autobiographical novel entitled ''Isola'', signed 'Ego' (her motto) \u2013 it was not a major success.<ref name=\"Match\"/> It did however generate quite a buzz, according to Catherine Hewitt: \"Thanks to the promotional skills of her contacts in the press, the book generated a wave of interest before it was even released [\u2026] Valtesse's diverse marketing strategies reaped immediate benefits; curious Parisians hurried out to purchase a copy of ''Isola''. It was a fiction, but all those who knew Valtesse could testify to its autobiographical quality.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Mistress of Paris|last=Hewitt|first=Catherine|publisher=Icon Books|year=2015|isbn=978-184831-926-4|location=London|pages=130\u2013132}}</ref> At least two editions can be found at the Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France, with [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k946266d/f13.image one digital copy] available to all. \"Ego\" had looked to the memoirs of C\u00e9leste de Chabrillan (published under the moniker Mogador) for inspiration: \"The volume gave the courtesan a chance to respond to her public's perception of her. With her memoirs, Mogador had seized control. Valtesse sensed an irresistible opportunity.  Not only would writing a book earn respect and provide an outlet for her creativity, it was a chance to shape her public image. She could dispel the myths she disliked and encourage those she approved.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Just as de Chabrillan's memoir's had influenced Valtesse's ''Isola'', \"Ego's\" autobiographical fiction would in turn inspire another courtesan's work: \"Liane de Pougy, roused in turn by her mentor's tome ''Isola'', would also contribute to the courtesan sub-genre in four novels she wrote during the Belle \u00c9poque. Born Anne-Marie Chassaigne, she renamed herself Liane de Pougy and earned notoriety  as a dancer and courtesan who engaged in several lesbian affairs (including one with de la Bigne) in fin de si\u00e8cle France.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Evolution of the French Courtesan Novel : From de Chabrillan to Colette|last=Sullivan, Courtney.|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=9781137597090|location=|pages=14|oclc=979829751}}</ref>\n\nAt the request of [[L\u00e9on Hennique]], she showed \u00c9mile Zola round her h\u00f4tel particulier. Her bedchamber and bed were the inspiration for those in his novel ''[[Nana (novel)|Nana]]'': \"A bed such as has never existed, a throne, an altar where Paris came to admire her sovereign nudity [...]. Along its sides, a band of cupids among flowers who look on and smile, watching the pleasures in shadows of the curtains.\" When she read the novel, Valtesse was indignant to find such a description of her decor \u2013 \"some traces of tender foolishness and gaudy splendour\".<ref>[http://www.alain-rustenholz.net/2011_05_01_archive.html Les Paris d'Alain Rustenholz], on ''alain-rustenholz.net'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref> and called the character of Nana (for which she was the inspiration) \"a vulgar whore, stupid, rude!\". Zola was still luckier than [[Alexandre Dumas fils]] \u2013 when the latter asked to enter her bedroom, she coldly replied \"Dear sir, it's not within your means!\"<ref>[[Armand Lanoux]], ''Bonjour Monsieur Zola'', Grasset, 1993, 409 pages, first edition, 1954 {{ISBN|2-246006-34-1}}.</ref>\n\n=== Artists' friend ===\n[[Image:\u00c9douard Manet - Mademoiselle Lucie Delabigne.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Valtesse de La Bigne, portrait by [[\u00c9douard Manet]], 1879, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City.]]\n[[Henri Gervex]] used her as the model for the courtesan in ''Civil Marriage'', which decorated the marriage room in the mairie of Paris's 19th arrondissement. She also inspired the heroine of ''La Nichina'', the novel by [[Hugues Rebell]], and the character Altesse in her friend and lover [[Liane de Pougy]]'s novel ''Idylle saphique''.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\nValtesse was a friend and sometime lover of [[\u00c9douard Manet]], [[Henri Gervex]], [[\u00c9douard Detaille]], [[Gustave Courbet]], [[Eug\u00e8ne Boudin]] and [[Alphonse de Neuville]], earning her the nicknames \"l'Union des Peintres\" or \"Altesse de la Guigne\". She posed for Manet, Gervex and Forain and Detaille lived near her on boulevard Malesherbes. She also talked with writers like [[Octave Mirbeau]], [[Ars\u00e8ne Houssaye]], [[Pierre Lou\u00ffs]], [[Th\u00e9ophile Gautier]] and [[Edmond de Goncourt]], inspiring his ''Ch\u00e9rie''.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\nA neighbour of [[L\u00e9on Gambetta]] in Ville-d'Avray, she asked to meet him. Although a Bonapartist, she argued with him that France should keep [[Tonkin]] \u2013 she knew its geopolitics via a correspondence with a former lover Alexandre de Kergaradec, French consul in Hano\u00ef, who had also sent her several gifts including a gigantic pagoda. On 9 June 1885 France recognised the French protectorate over Annam and Tonkin.\n\nShe amassed a vast art collection, later sold by auction between 2 and 7 June 1902 at the [[h\u00f4tel Drouot]].<ref>[http://www.osenat.fr/html/fiche.jsp?id=3408505&np=14&lng=fr&npp=20&ordre=1&aff=1&r= ''Psych\u00e9 aux renomm\u00e9es du Roi de Rome''], on ''osenat.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref> She left her vast bronze bed (created in 1877 by [[\u00c9douard Li\u00e8vre]]) to the [[mus\u00e9e des arts d\u00e9coratifs de Paris]],<ref>[http://www.robertopolo.com/media/polomedia/documents/art_press/32.pdf Edouard Li\u00e8vre : un cr\u00e9ateur des arts d\u00e9coratifs], on ''robertopolo.com'', consult\u00e9 le 20 ao\u00fbt 2014.</ref> still on display there.<ref>[http://www.lesartsdecoratifs.fr/francais/arts-decoratifs/collections-26/parcours-27/chronologique/xixe-siecle/les-salles-302/splendeurs-des-courtisanes/lit-de-parade-de-valtesse-de-la Lit de parade de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''lesartsdecoratifs.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\nShe drove a car, built the villa of Les Aigles in Monte-Carlo, sold her h\u00f4tel particulier on boulevard Malesherbes, whereupon she mainly lived in Ville-d'Avray, where she trained young women to become courtesans. Aged 62, one of her veins burst and she died shortly afterwards. She wrote her own death announcement, stating: \"One must love a little or a lot, following nature, but quickly, during an instant, as one loves a birdsong which speaks to one's soul and which one forgets with its last note, as one loves the crimson hues of the sun at the moment when it disappears below the horizon\". She was buried in the town cemetery with two unknown men<ref name=\"Match\"/><ref>[http://www.landrucimetieres.fr/spip/spip.php?article1705 Cimeti\u00e8re de Ville-d'Avray], on ''landrucimetieres.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>{{, }}.<ref>[http://www.tombes-sepultures.com/crbst_538.html Tombe de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''tombes-sepultures.com'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Portraits==\n\n* 1879 : by [[\u00c9douard Manet]], pastel, 55.2 x 35.6&nbsp;cm, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/436959 Mademoiselle Lucie Delabigne], on ''metmuseum.org'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n* 1889 : by [[Henri Gervex]], oil on canvas, [[mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], Paris<ref>[http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/collections/catalogue-des-oeuvres/notice.html?no_cache=1&nnumid=020569&cHash=cc04b411f6 Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay \u2013 Henri Gervex \u2013 Madame Valtesse de la Bigne], on ''musee-orsay.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography==\n\n* [[Catherine Hewitt]], ''The Mistress of Paris: The 19th-Century Courtesan Who Built an Empire on a Secret'', London, Icon Books, 2015, 320 pages, {{ISBN|978-184831-926-4}}.<ref>[http://www.iconbooks.com/blog/title/the-mistress-of-paris/ Icon Books >> The Mistress of Paris], on ''iconbooks.com'', accessed 7 September 2016.</ref>\n* [[Yolaine de La Bigne]], ''Valtesse de La Bigne ou le pouvoir de la volupt\u00e9'', Paris, Librairie acad\u00e9mique Perrin, 1999, 244 pages, {{ISBN|2-702834-76-0}}.<ref>[http://franckculture.wordpress.com/2013/03/07/lhistoire-de-valtesse-de-la-bigne-par-yolaine-de-la-bigne/ Histoire de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''franckculture.wordpress.com'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://data.bnf.fr/13510624/valtesse_de_la_bigne/ Valtesse de la Bigne] \u2013 [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]\n\n{{Prostitution in France|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Bigne, Valtesse de}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French courtesans]]\n[[Category:French prostitutes]]\n[[Category:French artists' models]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French stage actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = La Bigne, Valtesse.jpg\n| alt           = Valtesse de La Bigne, by Henri Gervex, mus\u00e9e d'Orsay, Paris\n| caption       = Valtesse de La Bigne, by [[Henri Gervex]], [[mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], Paris\n| birth_name    = \u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne\n| birth_date    = 1848\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| death_date    =  {{Death date|1910|07|29|df=y}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = French\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]], [[courtesan]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''\u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne''', known as countess '''Valtesse de La Bigne''' (1848, in [[Paris]] \u2013 29 July 1910,<ref>[http://data.bnf.fr/13510624/valtesse_de_la_bigne/ Valtesse de la Bigne \u2013 Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France].</ref> in [[Ville-d'Avray]]) was a French [[courtesan]] and [[demi-mondaine]].\n\n== Life ==\n\n===Youth and entry into prostitution===\nOne of six siblings, \u00c9milie-Louise was the daughter of a violent alcoholic father and a laundry maid from Normandy who worked as a prostitute. She worked in a Paris sweet-shop at age 10 and a dress shop at 13 when was raped in the street by an older man. She modelled for the painter [[Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot|Corot]], whose studio was in the district where she lived. At a young age she began work as a prostitute in the lorettes: \"respectable mistresses,\" between the lower class streetwalker or grisette and upper class courtesan. Nevertheless, this was still clandestine prostitution, often in doorways, and came with the risk of police arrest or having one's head shaved as punishment or humiliation.<ref name=\"Match\">[[Claire Castillon]], [http://www.parismatch.com/Royal-Blog/royaute-francaise/Valtesse-de-la-Bigne-coucher-pour-arriver-578894 \u00ab Valtesse de la Bigne, coucher pour arriver \u00bb], ''[[Paris Match]]'', week of 31 July-6 August 2014, pages 97\u2013100.</ref>\n\nQuickly moving onto rich clients, she trained at the [[Bal Mabille]] on Sundays and worked in a women's underwear shop on the Champ-de-Mars, frequented by high-ranking officers, enabling her to dream of social climbing. There she met and fell in love with a 20-year-old man, Richard Fossey, with whom she had two children, though Fossey left her to go to Algeria two years later without marrying her as he had promised. \n\nde La Bigne entrusted her two children to her mother who later on took them to live in the countryside. Following the death of her youngest daughter while in her mother's care, de La Bigne won a public court case against her mother who was allowing history to repeat itself as her granddaughter became increasingly drawn into the prostitution of France's demimonde. After winning custody of her one remaining daughter - with whom she fell pregnant aged 16 - de La Bigne had her placed into a Catholic boarding school. Later, bitter at her loss of regular income in lieu of providing childcare, her mother assaulted de La Bigne's housekeeper Camille, a childhood friend, who also took her to court but her case was thrown out. <ref> Catherine Hewitt, The Mistress of Paris.</ref>\n\n\u00c9milie-Louise Delabigne took the pseudonym 'Valtesse', due to its similarity to 'Votre Altesse' (your highness) \u2013 she later advised [[Liane de Pougy|Anne-Marie Chassaigne]] to take a pseudonym as well. She also resolved never to marry but to gain money and social position by other means. She profited from the 'br\u00e9siliens', foreign clients visiting Paris and aspired to join the 'archidr\u00f4lesses', a group of courtesans.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\n[[Jacques Offenbach]] brought Valtesse to public attention with a small role at the [[Bouffes-Parisiens]] and proposed that she act in his productions.<ref name=\"Match\"/> Her debut was as Hebe in ''[[Orph\u00e9e aux Enfers]]'' \u2013 one critic judged that she was \"as red and timid as a virgin by [[Titian]]\"\n\n=== 'Courtisane du Tout-Paris' ===\n[[File:\u00c9douard Li\u00e8vre Lit de parade de Valtesse de La Bigne c. 1875 Mus\u00e9e des arts d\u00e9coratifs Paris.jpg|thumb|Valtesse de La Bigne's show bed.]]\nShe became the composer's mistress and thus gained access to fashionable restaurants like Bignon (the former [[Caf\u00e9 de Foy]]) or the [[Caf\u00e9 Tortoni de Paris|Caf\u00e9 Tortoni]], where she met [[\u00c9mile Zola|Zola]], [[Gustave Flaubert|Flaubert]] and [[Guy de Maupassant|Maupassant]]. Even the starvation of the [[siege of Paris (1870)|siege of Paris]] did not dampen her aspirations \u2013 she was made a countess by [[Napoleon III]]. Known among the [[Tout-Paris]] for his scathing humour, the journalist and writer [[Aur\u00e9lien Scholl]] wrote: \"During the siege of Paris, all the women ate dog. It was thought that this nourishment taught them the principles of fidelity. Not at all! They demanded necklaces!\"<ref name=\"Match\"/><ref>[http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/aurelien-scholl-2694.php?citations Citations d'Aur\u00e9lien Scholl], on ''evene.lefigaro.fr'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref>\n\nAt the end of the war, Valtesse quickly launched herself as a high-class courtesan, leaving Offenbach and shifting her attentions to [[House of Lubomirski|prince Lubomirski]], who installed her in an apartment in rue Saint-Georges. She wrecked it, left him and had a succession of other rich lovers, such as [[Boson de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord|prince de Sagan]], whom she also bankrupted by having him build her a h\u00f4tel particulier designed by [[Jules F\u00e9vrier]] between 1873 and 1876 at 98, [[boulevard Malesherbes]], at the corner of [[rue de la Terrasse]] (destroyed and replaced by a residential block in 1904).<ref>[http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Valtesse-de-la-Bigne-coucher-pour-arriver-578894 \u00ab Valtesse de La Bigne : coucher pour arriver \u00bb], on ''parismatch.com'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref>\n\nNicknamed 'Rayon d'or' or 'golden ray', she immersed herself in art and literature. She bought a carriage to travel around Paris, and bought a sumptuous house at [[Ville-d'Avray]], which she decorated with paintings commissioned from [[\u00c9douard Detaille]] showing fictional members of her invented 'la Bigne family'.<ref name=\"Match\"/> In 1876 she published an autobiographical novel entitled ''Isola'', signed 'Ego' (her motto) \u2013 it was not a major success.<ref name=\"Match\"/> It did however generate quite a buzz, according to Catherine Hewitt: \"Thanks to the promotional skills of her contacts in the press, the book generated a wave of interest before it was even released [\u2026] Valtesse's diverse marketing strategies reaped immediate benefits; curious Parisians hurried out to purchase a copy of ''Isola''. It was a fiction, but all those who knew Valtesse could testify to its autobiographical quality.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Mistress of Paris|last=Hewitt|first=Catherine|publisher=Icon Books|year=2015|isbn=978-184831-926-4|location=London|pages=130\u2013132}}</ref> At least two editions can be found at the Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France, with [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k946266d/f13.image one digital copy] available to all. \"Ego\" had looked to the memoirs of C\u00e9leste de Chabrillan (published under the moniker Mogador) for inspiration: \"The volume gave the courtesan a chance to respond to her public's perception of her. With her memoirs, Mogador had seized control. Valtesse sensed an irresistible opportunity.  Not only would writing a book earn respect and provide an outlet for her creativity, it was a chance to shape her public image. She could dispel the myths she disliked and encourage those she approved.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Just as de Chabrillan's memoir's had influenced Valtesse's ''Isola'', \"Ego's\" autobiographical fiction would in turn inspire another courtesan's work: \"Liane de Pougy, roused in turn by her mentor's tome ''Isola'', would also contribute to the courtesan sub-genre in four novels she wrote during the Belle \u00c9poque. Born Anne-Marie Chassaigne, she renamed herself Liane de Pougy and earned notoriety  as a dancer and courtesan who engaged in several lesbian affairs (including one with de la Bigne) in fin de si\u00e8cle France.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Evolution of the French Courtesan Novel : From de Chabrillan to Colette|last=Sullivan, Courtney.|date=2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=9781137597090|location=|pages=14|oclc=979829751}}</ref>\n\nAt the request of [[L\u00e9on Hennique]], she showed \u00c9mile Zola round her h\u00f4tel particulier. Her bedchamber and bed were the inspiration for those in his novel ''[[Nana (novel)|Nana]]'': \"A bed such as has never existed, a throne, an altar where Paris came to admire her sovereign nudity [...]. Along its sides, a band of cupids among flowers who look on and smile, watching the pleasures in shadows of the curtains.\" When she read the novel, Valtesse was indignant to find such a description of her decor \u2013 \"some traces of tender foolishness and gaudy splendour\".<ref>[http://www.alain-rustenholz.net/2011_05_01_archive.html Les Paris d'Alain Rustenholz], on ''alain-rustenholz.net'', accessed 21 August 2014.</ref> and called the character of Nana (for which she was the inspiration) \"a vulgar whore, stupid, rude!\". Zola was still luckier than [[Alexandre Dumas fils]] \u2013 when the latter asked to enter her bedroom, she coldly replied \"Dear sir, it's not within your means!\"<ref>[[Armand Lanoux]], ''Bonjour Monsieur Zola'', Grasset, 1993, 409 pages, first edition, 1954 {{ISBN|2-246006-34-1}}.</ref>\n\n=== Artists' friend ===\n[[Image:\u00c9douard Manet - Mademoiselle Lucie Delabigne.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Valtesse de La Bigne, portrait by [[\u00c9douard Manet]], 1879, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City.]]\n[[Henri Gervex]] used her as the model for the courtesan in ''Civil Marriage'', which decorated the marriage room in the mairie of Paris's 19th arrondissement. She also inspired the heroine of ''La Nichina'', the novel by [[Hugues Rebell]], and the character Altesse in her friend and lover [[Liane de Pougy]]'s novel ''Idylle saphique''.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\nValtesse was a friend and sometime lover of [[\u00c9douard Manet]], [[Henri Gervex]], [[\u00c9douard Detaille]], [[Gustave Courbet]], [[Eug\u00e8ne Boudin]] and [[Alphonse de Neuville]], earning her the nicknames \"l'Union des Peintres\" or \"Altesse de la Guigne\". She posed for Manet, Gervex and Forain and Detaille lived near her on boulevard Malesherbes. She also talked with writers like [[Octave Mirbeau]], [[Ars\u00e8ne Houssaye]], [[Pierre Lou\u00ffs]], [[Th\u00e9ophile Gautier]] and [[Edmond de Goncourt]], inspiring his ''Ch\u00e9rie''.<ref name=\"Match\"/>\n\nA neighbour of [[L\u00e9on Gambetta]] in Ville-d'Avray, she asked to meet him. Although a Bonapartist, she argued with him that France should keep [[Tonkin]] \u2013 she knew its geopolitics via a correspondence with a former lover Alexandre de Kergaradec, French consul in Hano\u00ef, who had also sent her several gifts including a gigantic pagoda. On 9 June 1885 France recognised the French protectorate over Annam and Tonkin.\n\nShe amassed a vast art collection, later sold by auction between 2 and 7 June 1902 at the [[h\u00f4tel Drouot]].<ref>[http://www.osenat.fr/html/fiche.jsp?id=3408505&np=14&lng=fr&npp=20&ordre=1&aff=1&r= ''Psych\u00e9 aux renomm\u00e9es du Roi de Rome''], on ''osenat.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref> She left her vast bronze bed (created in 1877 by [[\u00c9douard Li\u00e8vre]]) to the [[mus\u00e9e des arts d\u00e9coratifs de Paris]],<ref>[http://www.robertopolo.com/media/polomedia/documents/art_press/32.pdf Edouard Li\u00e8vre : un cr\u00e9ateur des arts d\u00e9coratifs], on ''robertopolo.com'', consult\u00e9 le 20 ao\u00fbt 2014.</ref> still on display there.<ref>[http://www.lesartsdecoratifs.fr/francais/arts-decoratifs/collections-26/parcours-27/chronologique/xixe-siecle/les-salles-302/splendeurs-des-courtisanes/lit-de-parade-de-valtesse-de-la Lit de parade de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''lesartsdecoratifs.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\nShe drove a car, built the villa of Les Aigles in Monte-Carlo, sold her h\u00f4tel particulier on boulevard Malesherbes, whereupon she mainly lived in Ville-d'Avray, where she trained young women to become courtesans. Aged 62, one of her veins burst and she died shortly afterwards. She wrote her own death announcement, stating: \"One must love a little or a lot, following nature, but quickly, during an instant, as one loves a birdsong which speaks to one's soul and which one forgets with its last note, as one loves the crimson hues of the sun at the moment when it disappears below the horizon\". She was buried in the town cemetery with two unknown men<ref name=\"Match\"/><ref>[http://www.landrucimetieres.fr/spip/spip.php?article1705 Cimeti\u00e8re de Ville-d'Avray], on ''landrucimetieres.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>{{, }}.<ref>[http://www.tombes-sepultures.com/crbst_538.html Tombe de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''tombes-sepultures.com'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Portraits==\n\n* 1879 : by [[\u00c9douard Manet]], pastel, 55.2 x 35.6&nbsp;cm, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/436959 Mademoiselle Lucie Delabigne], on ''metmuseum.org'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n* 1889 : by [[Henri Gervex]], oil on canvas, [[mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], Paris<ref>[http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/collections/catalogue-des-oeuvres/notice.html?no_cache=1&nnumid=020569&cHash=cc04b411f6 Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay \u2013 Henri Gervex \u2013 Madame Valtesse de la Bigne], on ''musee-orsay.fr'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography==\n\n* [[Catherine Hewitt]], ''The Mistress of Paris: The 19th-Century Courtesan Who Built an Empire on a Secret'', London, Icon Books, 2015, 320 pages, {{ISBN|978-184831-926-4}}.<ref>[http://www.iconbooks.com/blog/title/the-mistress-of-paris/ Icon Books >> The Mistress of Paris], on ''iconbooks.com'', accessed 7 September 2016.</ref>\n* [[Yolaine de La Bigne]], ''Valtesse de La Bigne ou le pouvoir de la volupt\u00e9'', Paris, Librairie acad\u00e9mique Perrin, 1999, 244 pages, {{ISBN|2-702834-76-0}}.<ref>[http://franckculture.wordpress.com/2013/03/07/lhistoire-de-valtesse-de-la-bigne-par-yolaine-de-la-bigne/ Histoire de Valtesse de La Bigne], on ''franckculture.wordpress.com'', accessed 20 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://data.bnf.fr/13510624/valtesse_de_la_bigne/ Valtesse de la Bigne] \u2013 [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]\n\n{{Prostitution in France|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Bigne, Valtesse de}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French courtesans]]\n[[Category:French prostitutes]]\n[[Category:French artists' models]]\n", "name_user": "JaniceMSJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eYouth and entry into prostitution:several minor punctuation corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valtesse_de_La_Bigne"}
{"title_page": "Auckland City FC", "text_new": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club \n| clubname = Auckland City \n| website  = http://www.aucklandcityfc.com \n| current  = 2019\u201320 New Zealand Football Championship\n| image    = [[File:Auckland City.svg|200px|logo]] \n| fullname = Auckland City Football Club \n| nickname = City, The Navy Blues \n| short name = ACFC\n| founded  = {{Start date and age|2004}}<ref name=\"aucklandcityfc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/about-acfc/|title=About Auckland City Football Club|website=Auckland City FC|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> \n| ground   = [[Kiwitea Street]] \n| capacity = 3,500 \n| coordinates   = {{Coord|36|53|51|S|174|44|13|E|type:landmark_region:NZ_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| chairman = [[Ivan Vuksich]] \n| manager    = [[Jos\u00e9 Figueira]] \n| league   = [[New Zealand Football Championship]]\n| season   = [[2018\u201319 New Zealand Football Championship|2018\u201319]] \n| position = 1st (regular season), semi-finals (playoffs) \n|  pattern_la1=_acfc1617h|pattern_b1=_acfc1617h|pattern_ra1=_acfc1617h|pattern_sh1=_acfc1617h\n|  leftarm1=#002366|body1=#002366|rightarm1=#002366|shorts1=#002366|socks1=FFFFFF\n|  pattern_la2=_acfc1617a|pattern_b2=_acfc1617a|pattern_ra2=_acfc1617a|pattern_sh2=_acfc1617a\n|  leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=000040\n}}\n\n'''Auckland City Football Club''' is a New Zealand semi-professional [[Association football|football]] club based in the suburb of [[Sandringham, New Zealand|Sandringham]] in [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]. They currently compete in the [[New Zealand Football Championship|ISPS Handa Premiership]], the highest level of domestic football in New Zealand.<ref name=\"aucklandcityfc.com\"/> Auckland City have established themselves as a major force in both New Zealand and Oceania, having won seven [[New Zealand Football Championship|league titles]] and nine [[OFC Champions League]] titles since their foundation.<ref name=\"aucklandcityfc.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id154.htm|title=National League|website=www.ultimatenzsoccer.com|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nFormed in 2004 following the inception of the [[New Zealand Football Championship]], a brand new top level of domestic football in New Zealand, Auckland City currently play their home matches at [[Kiwitea Street]] in [[Sandringham, New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/contact/|title=Contact|website=Auckland City FC|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> The club is the most successful in [[Oceania Football Confederation|Oceania]] history, having won seven consecutive [[OFC Champions League]] titles between 2011 and 2017 - the most consecutive continental titles of any football team in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/live-scores/ofcchampionsleague/news/newsid/288/314/0/index.html|title=Seventh heaven for Auckland City|first=|last=FIFA.com|date=8 May 2017|website=FIFA.com|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> This has resulted in Auckland becoming a regular fixture at the [[FIFA Club World Cup]], famously achieving a [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup#Match for third place|third-placed]] finish in the [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup|2014 edition]].<ref name=\"stuff.co.nz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/64274495/null|title=Auckland City FC win international praise for Club World Cup effort|website=Stuff|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=259703/match=300298900/match-report.html|title=FIFA Club World Cup Morocco 2014 - Matches - Cruz Azul-Auckland City FC|first=|last=FIFA.com|website=FIFA.com|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> Auckland City's youth team formerly played in the [[National Youth League (New Zealand)|National Youth League]], becoming the most successful team in competition history with seven titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/57112?newsfeedId=569188&newsfeedPageNum=1|title=NYL \u2013 Auckland City claim title|website=www.nzfootball.co.nz|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAuckland City's regular [[Kit (association football)|kit]] colours are faintly striped royal blue shirts and shorts with white socks. The current crest, in use since the club's inception, features the [[Sky Tower (Auckland)|Sky Tower]], an iconic [[Auckland]] landmark. The club has a strong [[Croatian New Zealanders|Croatian]] influence, being strongly associated with and playing at the same stadium as [[Central United F.C.|Central United]] (formed in 1962 by [[Dalmatia]]n immigrants);\n\n==History==\n[[File:Amicale Vs Auckland City (1) (Imagicity 740).jpg|thumb|350|left|The Auckland City team in 2011]]\nAuckland City has won the regular season seven times, and the Grand Final six times. They represented the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] (OFC) in the [[OFC Champions League]], which they won most recently in 2017 for the ninth time (seventh in a row). With a third place in 2014, they also became the only OFC team to reach the semi-finals of the [[FIFA Club World Cup]]. They are also the only team to win the [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|continental treble]] three times.\n\nIn 2017, Auckland City were invited to play in the [[2017 Lunar New Year Cup|Lunar New Year Cup]], a friendly tournament hosted in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/national/88525420/Auckland-FC-get-invite-to-prestigious-Hong-Kong-tournament</ref> Auckland City defeated South Korean champions [[FC Seoul]] in the semifinal, before defeating Hong Kong side [[Kitchee SC|Kitchee]] in the final to lift the trophy.<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/88958905/auckland-city-fc-lift-nike-lunar-new-year-cup-in-hong-kong</ref> Auckland City were again invited for the [[2019 Lunar New Year Cup|2019 edition]], falling to [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C.|Shandong Luneng]] 2\u20131.<ref>https://www.hkfa.com/en/match/28088</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the [[2018\u201319 New Zealand Football Championship|2018\u201319 season]], in which Auckland City won all but one game in their undefeated season but fell short in both the [[OFC Champions League]] and the league playoffs, long-term manager [[Ramon Tribulietx]] brought his association with the club to an end and was replaced by [[Team Wellington]] coach [[Jos\u00e9 Figueira]] ahead of the [[2019\u201320 New Zealand Football Championship|2019\u201320 season]].<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/113267961/long-serving-auckland-city-fc-coach-ramon-tribulietx-leaves-club</ref><ref>https://www.aucklandcityfc.com/news/993/12/Jose-Figueira-named-Auckland-City-FC-coach-/</ref>\n\n===FIFA Club World Cup===\n\n; 2009\n{{main|2009 FIFA Club World Cup}}\nAuckland City overcame local champions [[Al-Ahli Dubai F.C.|Al Ahli]] 2\u20130 in the opening play-off match, with goals by Adam Dickinson and [[Chad Coombes]]. In their quarter final clash against [[CONCACAF]] champions [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] of Mexico, the side lost 0\u20133.\n\nThe play-off for fifth and sixth place was described by coach Paul Posa as \"the greatest night in the history of Auckland City Football Club\", as the team defeated [[CAF Champions League]] winners [[TP Mazembe]] of the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] 3\u20132. The goal scorers on this special occasion were Jason Hayne with two and [[Riki van Steeden]].\n\nThese historic victories were the first recorded by a New Zealand team at the Club World Cup, and the first by an amateur side at this tournament. This was also the first time that a senior men's representative team from New Zealand has recorded a victory in a world FIFA competition.\n\n; 2014\n{{main|2014 FIFA Club World Cup}}\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n|  GK_nat = New Zealand | GK = [[Jacob Spoonley|'''Spoonley''']]\n|  RB_nat = England | RB = '''White'''\n| RCB_nat = England | RCB = [[John Irving (footballer, born 1988)|'''Irving''']]\n| LCB_nat = Croatia | LCB = [[Mario Bilen|'''Bilen''']]\n|  LB_nat = Japan | LB = [[Takuya Iwata (footballer, born 1983)|'''Iwata''']]\n|  RCM_nat = New Zealand | RCM = [[Tim Payne (footballer)|'''Payne''']]\n|  DM_nat = New Zealand | DM = [[Ivan Vicelich|'''Vicelich''']]\n|  LCM_nat = New Zealand | LCM = '''Burfoot'''\n|  SS_nat = Mexico | SS = [[Fabrizio Tavano|'''Tavano''']]\n|  LF_nat = Argentina | LF = [[Emiliano Tade|'''Tade''']]\n|  RF_nat = New Zealand | RF = [[Ryan de Vries|'''de Vries''']]\n| caption = [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup#Match for third place|2014 FIFA Club World Cup third-placed playoff]] starting lineup\n}}\nAuckland City played [[2013\u201314 Botola|Moroccan]] league champions [[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]] in a play-off for the quarter-finals on 10 December. The match finished goalless, with Auckland winning 4\u20133 in a penalty shoot-out and qualifying for a quarter-final clash against [[AFC Champions League]] winners [[ES S\u00e9tif]].<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.goal.com/en/match/moghreb-t%C3%A9touan-vs-auckland-city/1956553/report |title=Moghreb 0 Auckland 0|date=10 December 2014|work=Goal.com|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> Auckland City defeated ES S\u00e9tif 1\u20130, courtesy of a [[John Irving (footballer, born 1988)|John Irving]] goal, and advanced to the semi-finals for the first time ever.\n\nAuckland played [[Copa Libertadores]] champions [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] in the semifinals, but lost 2\u20131. A shock seemed possible when a second-half goal from [[\u00c1ngel Berlanga]] cancelled out [[Pablo Barrientos]]' first-half strike for San Lorenzo, but substitute [[Mauro Matos]] netted San Lorenzo's winner in [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]].<ref name=\"stuff.co.nz\"/>\n\nThey finished the tournament with a historic 4-2 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] win over [[CONCACAF Champions League]] winners [[Cruz Azul]] in the third-place playoff after a 1\u20131 draw at full time, with substitute Sanni Issa scoring the ultimate penalty just days after signing for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=259693/match=300298897/match-report.html?intcmp=fifacom_hp_module_news|website=FIFA.com|title=Auckland sink Setif to book spot in semis|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-za/news/5008/club-world-cup/2014/12/21/7273642/maybe-now-theyll-know-me-in-nigeria-auckland-citys-club|title='Maybe now they'll know me in Nigeria!' - Auckland City's Club World Cup hero Sanni Issa - Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> The result gained the side worldwide acclaim, as the team of part-timers and amateurs defied all expectations in the competition. Club stalwart and defender [[Ivan Vicelich]] came third in the [[FIFA Club World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Golden Ball]] award for best player at the tournament, behind [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Sergio Ramos]] of [[Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/ramos-outshines-the-rest-2495409-2495436|title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2018 - News - Ramos outshines the rest - FIFA.com|first=|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Current players and staff==\n===First-team squad===\n{{updated|13 October 2019}}<ref>http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/players/premiership/</ref><ref>http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/news/1026/12/Tracey-penalty-save-inspires-friendly-win-/</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1 |nat=ESP|pos=GK|name=[[E\u00f1aut Zubikarai]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=2 |nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Mario Ilich}}\n{{Fs player|no=3 |nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=[[Adam Mitchell (footballer, born 1996)|Adam Mitchell]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=4 |nat=CRO|pos=MF|name=[[Mario Bilen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5 |nat=ESP|pos=DF|name=[[\u00c1ngel Berlanga]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6 |nat=VAN|pos=DF|name=[[Brian Kaltak]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7 |nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=[[Cameron Howieson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8 |nat=ESP|pos=MF|name=[[Albert Riera (footballer, born 1983)|Albert Riera]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9 |nat=NZL|pos=FW|name=[[Myer Bevan]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Dylan Manickum}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=[[Tom Doyle]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=ARG|pos=FW|name=[[Emiliano Tade]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Jordan Vale}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=IRQ|pos=MF|name=Yousif Ali Al-Kalisy}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=[[Andrew Blake (footballer)|Andrew Blake]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=NZL|pos=GK|name=Conor Tracey}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=NZL|pos=FW|name=[[Logan Rogerson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=COK|pos=FW|name=Maro Bonsu-Maro}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=[[Clayton Lewis (footballer)|Clayton Lewis]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Alfie Rogers}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=NZL|pos=GK|name=Cameron Brown}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Youth squad===\n\nAuckland City's youth squad currently competes in the [[National Youth League (New Zealand)|National Youth League]], and are the current champions, as well as the most successful side in the competition's history with six titles. They are managed by former New Zealand international [[Kris Bright]].<ref>http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/news/1017/12/Producing-players-is-our-aim-Kris-Bright-/</ref>\n{{updated|9 October 2019}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1 |nat=NZL|pos=GK|name=Sam Bottomley}}\n{{Fs player|no=2 |nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Nathan Lobo}}\n{{Fs player|no=3 |nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Jackson Woods}}\n{{Fs player|no=4 |nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Nicholas Milicich}}\n{{Fs player|no=5 |nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Dhanush Chandra}}\n{{Fs player|no=6 |nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Callum McNeill}}\n{{Fs player|no=7 |nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Matt Hodgson}}\n{{Fs player|no=8 |nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Miles Palmer}}\n{{Fs player|no=9 |nat=ZIM|pos=FW|name=Tawanda Marowa}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Matt Ellis}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=RSA|pos=MF|name=DeAndre Vollenhoven}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Jesse Gage}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Malcolm Young}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Colin Holthuis-Spann}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Harrison Freeman}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Corban Piper}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=NZL|pos=FW|name=Thomas Drillien}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=NZL|pos=GK|name=Luca Taylor}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|nat=NZL|pos=DF|name=Bradley Wilson}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Louis Middeldorp}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Finn McCracken}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=NZL|pos=MF|name=Micaiah Papa}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=NZL|pos=FW|name=Aidan Carey}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Coaching staff===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Position'''\n| \n|-\n|Manager\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jos\u00e9 Figueira]] \n|-\n|Assistant Manager\n||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Ivan Vicelich]]\n|-\n|Team Manager\n||{{flagicon|NZL}} Keith Coton\n|-\n|Goalkeeper Coach\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} Simone Naddi\n|-\n|Fitness Coach\n||{{flagicon|ESP}} Adri\u00e0 Casals\n|-\n|Technical Analyst\n||{{flagicon|NZL}} Jacob Weaver\n|-\n|Youth Manager\n|{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Kris Bright]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Medical staff===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Position'''\n|'''Name'''\n|-\n|Physiotherapist\n||{{flagicon|NZL}} Matt Payne<br>{{flagicon|IRL}} Danny Kelly\n|-\n|Club Doctor\n||{{flagicon|NZL}} Craig Panther\n|-\n|Massage Therapist\n||{{flagicon|POL}} Natalia Kozinska<br>{{flagicon|HUN}} Eva Nagy\n|-\n|}\n\n==Managers==\n*{{flagicon|England}} [[Allan Jones (football coach)|Allan Jones]] (2004\u20132006)\n*{{flagicon|New Zealand}} Roger Wilkinson (2006)\n*{{flagicon|New Zealand}} Paul Marshall (2006\u20132007)\n*{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Colin Tuaa]] (2007\u20132008)\n*{{flagicon|New Zealand}} Paul Posa (2008\u20132010)\n*{{flagicon|Vanuatu}} [[Aaron McFarland]] and {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ramon Tribulietx]] (2010\u20132011)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ramon Tribulietx]] (2011\u20132019)\n*{{flagicon|England}} [[Jos\u00e9 Figueira]] (2019\u2013)\n\n==Notable former players==\n\nThe following players gained international caps for their respective countries. Players listed in '''bold''' represented their countries while playing for Auckland City.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Teruo Iwamoto]]\n* {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Keryn Jordan]]\n* {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Grant Young (footballer)|Grant Young]]\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[Lee Ki-hyung]]\n* {{flagicon|SOL}} '''[[Micah Lea'alafa]]'''\n* {{flagicon|SOL}} '''[[Henry Fa'arodo]]'''\n* {{flagicon|SOL}} '''[[Nelson Sale Kilifa]]'''\n* {{flagicon|SOL}} '''[[George Suri]]'''\n* {{flagicon|Fiji}} '''[[Roy Krishna]]'''\n* {{flagicon|Fiji}} '''[[Salesh Kumar]]'''\n* {{flagicon|Vanuatu}} '''[[Brian Kaltak]]'''\n* {{flagicon|PNG}} [[David Browne (footballer)|David Browne]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[James Pritchett (footballer)|James Pritchett]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Cole Peverley]]\n{{col-3}}\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Paul Urlovic]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Nikko Boxall]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Michael Boxall]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Clayton Lewis (footballer)|Clayton Lewis]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Tim Payne (footballer)|Tim Payne]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Myer Bevan]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Jacob Spoonley]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Cameron Howieson]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Ian Hogg (footballer)|Ian Hogg]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Tom Doyle]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Sean Douglas (footballer)|Sean Douglas]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Adam McGeorge]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Jeff Campbell (footballer)|Jeff Campbell]]'''\n{{col-3}}\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Te Atawhai Hudson-Wihongi]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Liam Graham]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Tamati Williams]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Chad Coombes]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Dave Mulligan]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Ryan De Vries]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} '''[[Ivan Vicelich]]'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Matthew Ridenton]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Moses Dyer]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Kris Bright]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Ross Nicholson]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Jonathan Perry (footballer)|Jonathan Perry]]\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Harshae Raniga]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Kiwitea Street (Freyberg Field).jpg|thumb|Kiwitea Street in 2011]]\n{{main|Kiwitea Street}}\nFreyberg Field, then a public park, was made available for use as a football field in 1965 for tenants [[Central United F.C.|Central United]]. Following intense development on what became affectionately known as Kiwitea Street, the field quickly became one of the best playing surfaces in New Zealand, and was made available to Auckland City following their foundation in 2004. Since then, the amenities at Kiwitea Street have been overhauled, including a new clubrooms and a resurfaced pitch in 2007.\n\nThe stadium seats 250 spectators, with additional standing room.\n\n==Seasons==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! colspan=\"9\" | [[New Zealand Football Championship]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Finals series\n! colspan=\"2\" | Top goalscorer\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Managers\n|-\n! Div.\n! Pos.\n! Pl.\n! W\n! D\n! L\n! GS\n! GA\n! P\n! Name\n! League\n|-\n|align=center|[[2004\u201305 New Zealand Football Championship|2004\u201305]]\n|align=center|[[New Zealand Football Championship|1st]]\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"|'''1st'''\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|53\n|align=center|24\n|align=center|'''46'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"|'''Champions'''\n|alig