g)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* 2013 - [[Bernd Behr]], [[Chia-Wei Hsu]], [[Kate\u0159ina \u0160ed\u00e1]] and [[BATE\u017dO MIKILU]] (Curated by [[Esther Lu]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://universes.art/en/venice-biennale/2013/tour/taiwan/06/|title=Bernd Behr. Taiwan Pavilion|website=universes.art|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2015 - [[Wu Tien-chang]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://universes.art/en/venice-biennale/2015/tour/taiwan/|title=Taiwan Pavilion. Exhibitions & Pavilions|website=universes.art|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 - [[Tehching Hsieh]] (Curated by [[Adrian Heathfield]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://universes.art/en/venice-biennale/2017/taiwan/|title=Taiwan Pavilion. 57th Venice Biennale 2017|website=universes.art|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2019 - [[Shu Lea Cheang]] (Curated by [[Paul B. Preciado]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/496551/shu-lea-cheangs-installation-3x3x6-will-represent-taiwan-2019-venice-biennale/|title=Shu Lea Cheang\u2019s \"3x3x6\" Will Represent Taiwan at 2019 Venice Biennale|date=April 24, 2019|website=Hyperallergic|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Turkey===\nIn 2013, Turkey signed a 20-year lease for a national pavilion at the Venice Biennale. The state-funded Istanbul Foundation for Culture and Arts is the co-ordinator of the Turkish pavilion.<ref>Gareth Harris (December 26, 2013), [http://theartnewspaper.com/articles/Turkey-secures-national-pavilion-at-Venice-Biennale-until-/31394 Turkey secures national pavilion at Venice Biennale until 2034] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106185227/http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/Turkey-secures-national-pavilion-at-Venice-Biennale-until-/31394 |date=2014-01-06 }} ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref>\n\nList of exhibitors in the Turkish Pavilion:\n* 1990 \u2014 Kemal \u00d6nsoy, Mithat \u015een (Curator: Beral Madra)\n* 1993 \u2014 Erda\u011f Aksel, Serhat Kiraz, J\u0227rg Geismar, [[Adem Yilmaz]] (Curator: Beral Madra)\n* 2001 \u2014 Murat Morova, [[Butch Morris]], Ahmet \u00d6ktem, Sermin Sherif, Xurban.net (G\u00fcven Icirlio\u011flu & [[Hakan Topal]]) (Curator: Beral Madra)\n* 2003 \u2014 [[Nuri Bilge Ceylan]], Ergin \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu, G\u00fcl Ilgaz, Neriman Polat, Nazif Top\u00e7uo\u011flu (Curator: Beral Madra)\n* 2005 \u2014 [[Hussein Chalayan]] (Curator: Beral Madra)\n* 2007 \u2014 H\u00fcseyin Alptekin (Curator: [[Vasif Kortun]])\n* 2009 \u2014 [[Banu Cenneto\u011flu]], [[Ahmet \u00d6g\u00fct]] (Curator: [[Basak Senova]])\n* 2011 \u2014 [[Ay\u015fe Erkmen]] (Curator: Fulya Erdemci)\n* 2013 \u2014 [[Ali Kazma]] (Curator: Emre Baykal)\n* 2015 \u2014 [[Sarkis Zabunyan|Sarkis]] (Curator: Defne Ayas)<ref>Julia Halperin (August 5, 2014), [http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/Turkey-picks-Sarkis-for--Venice-Biennale/33363 Turkey picks Sarkis for 2015 Venice Biennale] ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref>\n* 2017 \u2014 [[Cevdet Erek]]<ref>Robin Scher (April 26, 2016), [http://www.artnews.com/2016/04/26/cevdet-erek-will-represent-turkey-at-the-2017-venice-biennale/ Cevdet Erek Will Represent Turkey at the 2017 Venice Biennale] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* 2019 \u2014 \u0130nci Eviner (Curator: Zeynep \u00d6z)\n\n===Tuvalu===\nDespite the cost to the third world country, [[Tuvalu]] decided to develop its first national pavilion in 2013 to highlight the negative effects of global warming on the nation, which is forecast to be one of the first countries to disappear due to sea level rise caused by climate change.<ref name=\"radioaustralia.net.au\">{{cite web |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Company Radio Australia |title=Tuvalu Takes Climate Threat to Venice Biennale |url=http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/radio/program/pacific-beat/Tuvalu-takes-climate-threat-to-venice-biennale/1145208}}</ref> After working closely with Taiwanese eco artist [[Vincent J.F. Huang]] at the 2012 [[UNFCCC]] COP18 session in [[Doha, Qatar]] and collaborating with the artist on several occasions, Tuvalu's government invited Huang to act as the representative artist for the pavilion.<ref name=\"radioaustralia.net.au\"/> All of the artworks at the 2013 Tuvalu Pavilion focused on climate change and included ''[[In the Name of Civilization]]'', a giant oil rig turned agent of destruction, and ''[[Prisoner's Dilemma]]'', a depiction of the Statue of Liberty kneeling in apology to ghostly portraits of terra-cotta penguins symbolic of ecological sacrifices made to further the development of human civilization.<ref>Tuvalu Pavilion, ed., ''Tuvalu Pavilion: 55th International Art Exhibition-la Biennale di Venezia'', Taipei: Xin Chuan Cultural Foundation</ref>\n\nList of exhibitors for the Tuvalu Pavilion:\n* 2013 \u2014 Vincent J.F. Huang (Curators: An-Yi Pan, Li Szuhsien, Shih Shuping)\n* 2015 \u2014 Vincent J.F. Huang (Curator: Thomas J. Berghuis)\n\n===Ukraine===\nThe [[PinchukArtCentre]] sponsored Ukraine's pavilions in 2007, 2009 and 2015.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nList of exhibitors in the Ukrainian Pavilion:\n* 2005 \u2014 [[Mykola Babak]] \u00abYour Children, Ukraine\u00bb (Curator: Oleksiy Tytarenko)\n* 2011 \u2014 [[Oksana Mas]] \u00abPost-vs-Proto-Renaissance\u00bb (Curator: Oleksiy Rogotchenko)\n* 2013 \u2014 Ridnyi Mykola, Zinkovskyi Hamlet, Kadyrova Zhanna (Curators: Soloviov Oleksandr, Burlaka Victoria)\n* 2015 \u2014 Yevgenia Belorusets, Nikita Kadan, Zhanna Kadyrova, Mykola Ridnyi & Serhiy Zhadan, Artem Volokitin, Anna Zvyagintseva and Open Group (Curator: Bj\u00f6rn Geldhof)\n* 2017 \u2014 [[Boris Mikhailov (photographer)|Boris Mikhailov]] (Curator: [[Peter Doroshenko]])\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\nThe United Arab Emirates' Venice pavilion first opened in 2009, but 2015 was the first time an Emirati has served as curator.\n\nList of exhibitors in the UAE Pavilion:\n* 2009 \u2014 Lamya Gargash (Commissioner: Dr Lamees Hamdan; Curator: Tirdad Zolghadr) \n* 2011 \u2014 Abdullah Al Saadi, Sheikha Lateefa bint Maktoum, Reem Al Ghaith (Curator: Vasif Kortun)\n* 2013 \u2014 [[Mohammed Kazem]] (Commissioner: Dr. Lamees Hamdan; Curator: Reem Fadda)\n* 2015 \u2014 [[Hassan Sharif]], [[Mohammed Kazem]], [[Abdullah Al Saadi]], Ahmed Al Ansari, [[Moosa Al Halyan]], Mohammed Al Qassab, [[Abdul Qader Al Rais]], Mohammed Abdullah Bulhiah, Salem Jawhar, [[Najat Makki|Dr. Najat Makki]], [[Abdulraheem Salim]], Obaid Suroor, Dr. Mohamed Yousif, and Abdulrahman Zainal (Curator: Hoor Al Qasimi)<ref>Laura van Straaten (January 27, 2015), [http://theartnewspaper.com/articles/UAE-announces-group-show-with--artists-for-its-Venice-pavilion/36977 UAE announces group show with 14 artists for its Venice pavilion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130020815/http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/UAE-announces-group-show-with--artists-for-its-Venice-pavilion/36977 |date=2015-01-30 }} ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref>\n*2017 \u2014 [[Nujoom Al-Ghanem]], Sara Al Haddad, Vikram Divecha, Lantian Xie, Mohamed Yousif. (Curator: Hammad Nasar)\n* 2019 \u2014 Nujoom Al-Ghanem <ref>Alex Greenberger (January 29, 2019), [http://www.artnews.com/2019/01/29/nujoom-alghanem-will-represent-united-arab-emirates-2019-venice-biennale/ Nujoom Alghanem Will Represent United Arab Emirates at 2019 Venice Biennale] ''[[ARTnews]]''</ref> (Curators: Sam Bardaouil and Till Fellrath) <ref> Dennis Mao (October 3, 2018), [http://artasiapacific.com/News/SamBardaouilAndTillFellrathNamedCuratorsOfThe2019VeniceBiennaleUAENationalPavilion]''[[ArtAsiaPacific]]''</ref>\n\n===Wales===\nThe Wales pavilion was introduced in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncilofwales.org.uk/artsinwales/venice |title=Cymru yn Fenis Wales in Venice 2013 |publisher=Arts Council of Wales |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org/uk-in-venice |title=British Council \u2212 British Pavilion in Venice |publisher=Venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113081408/http://venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org/uk-in-venice |archivedate=2013-11-13 }}</ref>\n\nList of exhibitors in the Wales Pavilion:\n* 2003 \u2014 [[Bethan Huws]]<ref name=\"Sherwin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/mar/02/artist-of-week-bethan-huws|title=Artist of the week 128: Bethan Huws|last=Sherwin|first=Skye|date=2 March 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref> & [[Cerith Wyn Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/venice-biennale/ |title=Wales \u2013 Arts \u2013 Venice Biennale \u2013 Wales at the Venice Biennale |publisher=BBC |date=2010-10-06 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref> & Simon Pope [http://sites.google.com/site/ambulantscience/Curriculum-Vitae Simon Pope | Art Work - About]\n* 2005 \u2014 Peter Finnemore, [[Laura Ford]] & Paul Granjon<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/somewhere-else-artists-from-wales/ |title=Somewhere Else: Artists from Wales |publisher=e-flux |date=2005-05-28 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/whatson/?event_id=5767 |title=What's on &#124; National Museum Wales |publisher=Museumwales.ac.uk |date=2012-04-25 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artswales.org.uk/what-we-do/funding/creative-wales/awards-2012-13/paul-granjon |title=Arts Council of Wales &#124; Paul Granjon |publisher=Artswales.org.uk |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201145256/http://www.artswales.org.uk/what-we-do/funding/creative-wales/awards-2012-13/paul-granjon |archivedate=2014-02-01 }}</ref>\n* 2007 \u2014 [[Richard Deacon (sculptor)|Richard Deacon]], [[Merlin James]], & Heather and Ivan Morison<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/6735141.stm | work=BBC News | title=Welsh artists at Venice Biennale | date=June 10, 2007}}</ref>\n* 2009 \u2014 [[John Cale]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org/people/reference/john-cale |title=British Council \u2212 British Pavilion in Venice |publisher=Venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203011356/http://venicebiennale.britishcouncil.org/people/reference/john-cale |archivedate=2014-02-03 }}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2014 Tim Davies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wai.org.uk/news/2235 |title=Wales Arts International &#124; Wales at the Venice Biennale of Art |publisher=Wai.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2014 [[Bedwyr Williams]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-22736582|title=Venice Biennale: Bedwyr Williams looks to the stars|last=Thomas|first=Huw|date=1 June 2013|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2014 [[Helen Sear]] (Curator: Ffotogallery)\n* 2017 \u2014 [[James Richards (artist)|James Richards]]<ref>Alex Greenberger (May 26, 2016), [http://www.artnews.com/2016/05/26/james-richards-will-represent-wales-at-the-2017-venice-biennale/ James Richards Will Represent Wales at the 2017 Venice Biennale] ''[[ARTnews]]''</ref>\n* 2019 \u2014 Sean Edwards (Curator: Marie-Anne McQuay)\n\n===Zimbabwe===\n* 2011 \u2014 [[Tapfuma Gutsa]], [[Misheck Masamvu]], [[Berry Bickle]], [[Calvin Dondo]] (Commissioner: [[Doreen Sibanda]]; curator: [[Raphael Chikukwa]])\n* 2013 \u2014 [[Portia Zvavahera]], [[Michele Mathison]], [[Rashid Jogee]], [[Voti Thebe]], [[Virginia Chihota]] (Commissioner: Doreen Sibanda; curator: [[Raphael Chikukwa]])\n* 2015 \u2014 [[Chikonzero Chazunguza]], [[Masimba Hwati]], [[Gareth Nyandoro]] (Commissioner: Doreen Sibanda; curator: Raphael Chikukwa)\n* 2017 \u2014 [[Charles Bhebe]], [[Admire Kamudzengerere]], [[Sylvester Mubayi]], [[Dana Whabira]] (Commissioner: Doreen Sibanda; curator: Raphael Chikukwa)\n* 2019 \u2014 [[Kudzanai-Violet Hwami]], [[Neville Starling]], [[Georgina Maxim]], [[Cosmas Shiridzinomwa]] (Commissioner: Doreen Sibanda; curator: Raphael Chikukwa)<ref>Andrew Russeth (February 19, 2019), [http://www.artnews.com/2019/02/19/zimbabwe-pavilion-venice-biennale-2019/ Zimbabwe Taps Four for 2019 Venice Biennale Pavilion] ''[[ARTnews]]''</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Martino\">Martino, Enzo Di. ''The History of the Venice Biennale''. Venezia: Papiro Arte, 2007.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Farah Nayeri (May 10, 2015), [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/11/arts/design/venice-biennale-pavilions-for-iraq-ukraine-and-syria-reflect-strife-at-home.html Venice Biennale Pavilions for Iraq, Ukraine and Syria Reflect Strife at Home] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Russeth |first1=Andrew |title=The Venice Biennale: Everything You Could Ever Want to Know |work=[[ARTnews]] |date=2019-04-17 |url=http://www.artnews.com/2019/04/17/the-venice-biennale-everything-you-could-ever-want-to-know/ |language=en-US |accessdate=2019-04-22 |df=mdy-all |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Volpi |first=Cristiana |chapter=Pavilions/Historical Background|editor-last1=Re Rebaudengo |editor-first1=Adele |year=2013 |title=Pavilions and Garden of Venice Biennale |pages=163\u2013195 |publisher=Contrasto |location=Rome |isbn=978-88-6965-440-4 |ref=harv }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Droitcour |first1=Brian |title=Pavilion Problems |work=[[Art in America]] |date=2015-08-28 |url=https://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/magazines/pavilion-problems/ |language=en-US |accessdate=2018-06-20 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Mulazzani |first1=Marco |title=Guida ai padiglioni della Biennale di Venezia dal 1887 |date=2014 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-918-0052-7 |publisher=Electa architettura |location=Milano |oclc=963880895 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Venice Biennale}}\n{{coords|45.429|12.358|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:National pavilions| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Biennale art 2011 Giardini near the Brit pavilion.jpg|thumb|Crowds near the British pavilion in 2011]]\nThe '''national pavilions''' host each participant nation's official representation during the [[Venice Biennale]], an international [[art biennial]] exhibition held in [[Venice, Italy]]. Some countries own pavilion buildings in the [[Giardini della Biennale]] while others rent buildings throughout the city, but each country controls its own selection process and production costs.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Background ==\nThe Venice Biennale is an international [[art biennial]] exhibition held in [[Venice, Italy]]. Often described as \"the Olympics of the [[art world]]\", participation in the Biennale is a prestigious event for contemporary artists. The festival has become a constellation of shows: a central exhibition curated by that year's artistic director, national pavilions hosted by individual nations, and independent exhibitions throughout Venice. The Biennale parent organization also hosts regular festivals in other arts: architecture, dance, film, music, and theater.{{sfn|Russeth|2019}}\n\nOutside of the central, international exhibition, individual nations produce their own shows, known as pavilions, as their national representation. Nations that own their pavilion buildings, such as the 30 housed on the Giardini, are responsible for their own upkeep and construction costs as well. Nations without dedicated buildings create pavilions in venues throughout the city.{{sfn|Russeth|2019}}\n\n== Giardini national pavilions ==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Nation\n! Location\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | First exhibition\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Year of construction{{sfn|Volpi|2013}}\n<!--|-\n| [[Angolan pavilion|Angola]] || Throughout city ||  || \u2014-->\n|-\n| [[Austrian pavilion|Austria]] || Giardini ||  || 1934\n|-\n| [[Australian pavilion|Australia]] || Giardini ||  || 1988\n|-\n| [[Belgian pavilion|Belgium]] || Giardini |